h his column faltering under close artillery fire, Phelps rode to its head and led the assault to within feet of the Confederate works — where he fell severely wounded and was captured. His citation says he placed himself conspicuously in front of the troops."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"The Medal of Honor came thirty-four years late","body":"The charge was 1864; the Medal of Honor arrived March 30, 1898, when Phelps was a sixty-four-year-old Baltimore judge. He had passed through four political parties and three careers in the interval."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"His mother wrote the nation’s science textbooks","body":"Phelps was the son of Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps, whose botany and chemistry textbooks taught a generation of American students, and the nephew of Emma Hart Willard, the pioneer of women’s education. The family’s Hart line runs back to Farmington."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"His half-brother was outlawed by Davis","body":"Charles’s father’s son by his first wife, Gen. John Wolcott Phelps, armed fugitive slaves at New Orleans in 1862 — for which Jefferson Davis declared him an outlaw — returned his commission to Lincoln on principle, and polled 1,045 votes for President in 1880. The half-brothers each wore Union stars."}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM835","plot_notes":"Woodlawn Cemetery (PM) (N-130)"},"career":[{"role":"Member","organization":"Baltimore City Council","start_year":1860,"end_year":1861},{"role":"US Representative","organization":"Maryland 3rd District","start_year":1865,"end_year":1869},{"role":"Judge","organization":"Circuit Court of Baltimore","start_year":1882,"end_year":1908}],"number_of_marriages":1,"slug":"charles-phelps-1833"},"X03188":{"id":"X03188","bio":{"display_name":"Martha Woodward Phelps","gender":"female","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781198824/martha_eq6xla.png"},"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_