) married three daughters of Hon. John Hooker (H00030). Lieut. Samuel Hart married I00029's wife's sister Sarah Hooker (H00101, b.~1701); she had married Matthew Hart in 1726."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"Three Hart brothers each married a Hooker sister","body":"He was one of three sons of Capt. John Hart who each married a daughter of John Hooker Esq. of Farmington — Nathaniel married Abigail, Samuel married Mary, and Matthew married Sarah, between 1719 and 1725, binding two of Farmington's founding families."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Died when his only son was fourteen","body":"Lieut. Samuel Hart had planned a collegiate education for his only son Samuel, but died when the boy was about fourteen. His widow, unwilling to part with him, kept him home and provided the best education locally available."}],"baptism":{"year":1692,"month":9,"day":18,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"bio":{"title":"Lieutenant","display_name":"Lieut. Samuel Hart","first_name":"Samuel","last_name":"Hart","married_names":[]},"landmarks":[],"residence":{"city":"Berlin","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"samuel-hart-1692"},"H00100":{"id":"H00100","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":4,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1700,"month":7,"day":11,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1780,"month":11,"day":22,"city":"Worthington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00030","mother_id":"I00031"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00029","children_ids":["H00277","H00278","H00279","H00280","H00281"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1723,"date_month":12,"date_day":25,"location_country":"United States"}],"open_questions":[{"question":"Elihu Burritt descent through this line","status":"closed","notes":"CLOSED: Elihu Burritt's Hooker descent through this line is NOT CONFIRMED. His connection to the tree is through KINSHIP, not descent: his grandfather Elijah Hinsdale (X01931) and Lydia Hinsdale Hart (I00034) were siblings — both children of Capt. John Hinsdale (X00039). This makes Burritt the first cousin once removed of Emma Hart Willard (H00597) and Almira Hart Phelps (H00598). The claim that Burritt descended from Thomas Hooker through Huldah Hart (H00280) could not be traced through available sources. He is documented in the tree as an orbit_notable (X01932) with the Hinsdale kinship connection noted.","action":"No further action needed."}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 100"},{"short":"Phelps/NYGB 1843","full":"Mrs. Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps, article on Hart family, New York Genealogical and Biographical Record","url":"https://www.newyorkfamilyhistory.org/online-records/nygb-record/566-074/16","author":"Mrs. Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps (1793-1884), youngest daughter of Capt. Samuel Hart of Kensington, granddaughter of Lieut. Samuel Hart and Mary (Hooker) Hart"}],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":null,"primary_url":null,"primary_url_label":null},"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"I00028","display_label":"Brother-in-law via Hart-Hooker triple marriage, 1719-1726","link_text":"Nathaniel Hart","notes":"One of the three Hart-Hooker marriages between 1719 and 1726: three daughters of Hon. John Hooker (H00030) married three sons of Capt. John Hart (X00033). Nathaniel Hart married Mary Hooker's sister Abigail Hooker (H00099) in 1719; Mary Hooker married I00029 in 1723."},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"I00030","display_label":"Brother-in-law via Hart-Hooker triple marriage, 1719-1726","link_text":"Matthew Hart","notes":"One of the three Hart-Hooker marriages between 1719 and 1726: three daughters of Hon. John Hooker (H00030) married three sons of Capt. John Hart (X00033). Matthew Hart married Mary Hooker's sister Sarah Hooker (H00101) in 1726; Mary Hooker married I00029 in 1723."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"She and her sisters all married Hart brothers","body":"She was one of three daughters of John Hooker Esq. of Farmington who each married a son of Capt. John Hart — Abigail to Nathaniel, Mary to Samuel, and Sarah to Matthew — between 1719 and 1725, uniting the two most prominent families of Farmington's founding generation."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Hooker Hart","first_name":"Mary","last_name":"Hart","married_names":["Hart"],"maiden_name":"Hooker"},"landmarks":[],"residence":{"city":"Worthington Parish (now Berlin)","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"mary-hart-1700"},"X00039":{"id":"X00039","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1706,"month":8,"day":13,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1792,"month":12,"day":2,"city":"New Britain","state":"Connecticut"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00040","children_ids":["I00034","X01931"],"marriage_number":1}],"sources":[{"short":"Hinsdale Genealogy","notes":"Entry for Capt. John Hinsdale"}],"parents":{"mother_research_notes":"Martha Smith","father_research_notes":"Barnabas Hinsdale Jr."},"children_noted":["John (b.1734, d. Oct 13, 1743)","Elizabeth (b.1736, m. David Atkins of Middletown 1758, d.1772)","Theodore/Rev. (b.1738, m. Anna Bissell)","Lucy (b.1741, m. Samuel Plumb)","Elijah (b.1744, m. twice)","Lydia (b.1747, m. Samuel Hart) — mother of Emma Hart Willard","John Jr. (b.1749, m. Philomela Hurlbut)"],"gender":"male","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","display_label":"Father-in-law of Capt. Samuel Hart — grandfather of Emma Hart Willard's mother","related_id":"H00281","link_text":"Capt. Samuel Hart"},{"type":"family_connection","display_label":"Father-in-law of Capt. Samuel Hart — grandfather of Emma Hart Willard's mother","related_id":"I00034","link_text":"Lydia Hinsdale Hart"},{"type":"family_connection","display_label":"Father-in-law of Capt. Samuel Hart — grandfather of Emma Hart Willard's mother","related_id":"H00597","link_text":"Emma Hart Willard"},{"type":"family_connection","display_label":"Father-in-law of Capt. Samuel Hart — grandfather of Emma Hart Willard's mother","related_id":"H00598","link_text":"Almira Hart Phelps"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Grandfather of Emma Hart Willard and Almira Phelps","body":"His daughter Lydia Hinsdale married Capt. Samuel Hart in 1770 — their daughters Emma Hart Willard founded Troy Female Seminary as a pioneer of women's education, and Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps wrote textbooks read by generations. Both granddaughters became among the most consequential 19th-century American educators."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Great-grandfather of the Learned Blacksmith","body":"His son Elijah Hinsdale was the grandfather of Elihu Burritt, the New Britain blacksmith who became internationally famous as 'the Learned Blacksmith' — a self-taught polyglot who founded the League of Universal Brotherhood. Burritt was thus first cousin once removed to Emma Hart Willard and Almira Phelps."},{"number":3,"category":"military","header":"Ensign to Captain in the Connecticut Trained Band","body":"He rose through the ranks of Connecticut's 6th Regiment, 15th Company — Ensign in 1749, Lieutenant in 1752, Captain in 1759. He was described as a man of rare military and literary ability."},{"number":4,"category":"career","header":"Blacksmith with a shop on Berlin Street","body":"He worked as a blacksmith from a shop near his house, opposite what would become the Methodist Church on Berlin Street, New Britain. In 1781 he bought the 70-acre Deacon Josiah Lee farm from John Richards."}],"military_service":[{"rank":"Captain","notes":"Captain of 15th Company, 6th Regiment, CT Militia."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Captain John Hinsdale","title":"Captain","first_name":"John","last_name":"Hinsdale","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"slug":"john-hinsdale-1706"},"X00040":{"id":"X00040","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{},"death":{},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00039","children_ids":["I00034","X01931"],"marriage_number":1}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 281"}],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Elizabeth Cole Hinsdale","first_name":"Elizabeth","last_name":"Hinsdale","married_names":["Hinsdale"],"maiden_name":"Cole"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"elizabeth-cole"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{"INST066":{"id":"INST066","primary_name":"Troy Female Seminary (Emma Willard School)","name":"Troy Female Seminary (Emma Willard School)","short_name":"Troy Female Seminary","alt_names":[],"type":"seminary","founding_year":1814,"location":{"city":"Troy","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emma_Willard_School","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia","primary_persons":["H00597"],"hooker_connected_people":["H00597","H00598","HD2963","HD2964","HD3148"],"person_ids":["X02107"],"related_institutions":[],"related_landmarks":[],"tags":[],"sources":[],"notes":"Founded 1814 by Emma Hart Willard (H00597) in Middlebury, VT as the Middlebury Female Seminary — the first women's higher education institution in the United States. Moved to Troy, NY in 1821 and renamed Troy Female Seminary. Renamed Emma Willard School in 1895. Willard resigned leadership in 1838 to her son John Willard (H01550). Almira Hart Phelps (H00598) was vice-principal; wrote Lectures on Botany (1829) during this tenure — 10,000 copies sold in three years. Twelve or more Berlin CT girls attended on Willard's invitation and expense, including Jane Porter Hart (HD2963) and Harriet Hart (HD2964). As of 2026: endowment $119M; grades 9-12 plus postgraduate; #1 private school Upstate NY 2018.\n[former/alt detail] Formerly: Middlebury Female Seminary (1814); Troy Female Seminary (1821). Now: Emma Willard School."}},"crossConnections":[{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"HD3148","link_text":"Eunice Newton Foote","display_label":"Her student Eunice Newton Foote published the first greenhouse effect paper in.","slug":"eunice-foote-1819"}]}